347. reddantur, ordinary conditional subjunctive: the sense is ‘has won the meed in vain, should the first place be given to Salius’. The indicative in apodosis is perfectly natural, owing to the sense, which is a little compressed. If expanded into the strict conditional form it would be: ‘he has won the meed, and his winning would be vain, if the first place &c.' Such formal irregularities of the conditional sentence, due to rapidity of style or substitution of something else for the proper apodosis, are vcry common, e.g. memini numeros si verba tenerem Ecl. 9. 45, multa. me dehortantur ni studium superet Sall.
